Kickoff discussion results:

@remcowesterhoud Clarify that we don't like the Job Extend Lock as it's not really a locking mechanism in intro ✅
@remcowesterhoud Change naming from deadline to timeout to keep it aligned with job activation ✅
@remcowesterhoud Change naming from Change to Update ✅
@remcowesterhoud Check what happens if we have the UPDATE_TIMEOUT on the log, and also a TIMEOUT already after this.

No issue here, TIMEOUT Processor checks if deadline actually expired ✅


@remcowesterhoud If we can't find the deadline consider returning an INVALID_STATE (?), something other that a NOT_FOUND. ✅
@remcowesterhoud Add a timeoutProperty to the JobRecord ✅

@remcowesterhoud I suggest changing the name to Update Job Deadline. While the user specifies a timeout, the engine uses it to determine a new job deadline and update it accordingly. I think it best fits the topic.
This would also help avoid confusion with Job Backoff (which in theory is also a timeout keeping the job not-activatable but during the failed state).

@korthout I just updated everything 😭
But really, I'm not sure if it's better. When activating jobs users also specify a timeout, which in turn sets a deadline. Users always work using the term timeout. The only time they see deadline is in the activate job response, which is likely hidden behind a job worker. I'm not convinced naming it UpdateJobDeadline is better tbh.

